 a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Louis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hlōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>wīg</i> ‘war’. It was very common in French royal and noble families.  Louis I  (  778–840 ) was the son of Charlemagne, who ruled as both King of France and Holy Roman Emperor. Altogether, the name was borne by sixteen kings of France up to the French Revolution, in which Louis XVI perished. Louis XIV, ‘the Sun King’ (  1638–1715 ), reigned for seventy-two years (  1643–1715 ), presiding in the middle part of his reign over a period of unparalleled French power and prosperity. In modern times Louis is also found in the English-speaking world (usually pronounced ‘<b>loo</b>-ee’). In Britain the Anglicized form   Lewis   is rather more common, whereas in America the reverse is true."],"variants":[{"name":"Lewie","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of   Louis  , or a pet form of   Lewis ."]},{"name":"Louie","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Lewie   or   Louis  , currently in fashion."]},{"name":"Lewi","meanings":["form, since the Middle Ages, of the French name   Louis .  In modern use it is also in part a transferred use of the surname derived from this given name, or from Anglicized forms of Gaelic <i>Mac Lughaidh</i> ‘son of  <b>Lughaidh</b> ’  or Welsh Llewelyn ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Louis de Bernieulle II was born in 1201, in Bernieulles, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, his father, Louis de Bernieulle I, was 28 and his mother, Péronne de Brimeu, was 18. He had at least 1 daughter with Havoise DE NEUCHATEL HARDELOT. He died in 1249, in his hometown, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1201–1249":"1201–1249","1211–1267":"1211–1267","1228–1286":"1228–1286","1231–1289":"1231–1289","1173–1229":"1173–12